up|3|

nt|^b@2^z@3It's a different story if West applies cover an honor with an honor and plays his @DK on South's lead of @DJ. |
pg| ***** 158 ***** |


pc|dkdd|
pg| ***** 159 ***** |


wt|s|at|The only remaining test for the defense is that, if South later leads the @D8 from his hand, |
pg| ***** 160 ***** |


pc|d8|at|West must remember to split his @D109 |
pg| ***** 161 ***** |


at|(splitting low with the @D9 as we do in this program). |
pg| ***** 162 ***** |


pc|d9|at|^^^^The dummy's @DQ will be trapped and the declarer will not be able to win a trick in diamonds.|
pg| ***** 163 ***** |


up|6|md|1cj,cq873,ca|



nt|^b@2^z@3Let's look at a few situations where a defender should know that it would be a bad idea to cover an honor with an honor. In the example shown above, South leads the @CJ. |
pg| ***** 164 ***** |


pc|cj|at|It should be easy for West to realize that covering the @CJ with the @CQ would be a poor play. |
pg| ***** 165 ***** |


at|^^^^Regardless of the club that West plays, the singleton @CA is going to have to be played from the dummy. West should simply play second hand low. There is no reason to waste the @CQ. |
